She turned to a blank page and noted the date. Below that, she wrote "11/05/648 - 13/12/648."
"Are you re-reading memories?", Ivory inquired, looking at the old notebook. Kari nodded her head. "Do you think they'll let you out for Christmas? It's just a few days away."
Kari knocked twice on the lantern. No. Ivory had been right. The King of Ice never let Kari out, for she was "an error" in his eyes. She was born mute, and she was the only daughter of the family, which was otherwise composed entirely of boys.
Ivory was one too, in her own way. When she had spoken of her non-binariness, it was as if the world had changed along with her. They had been given tasks that condemned her to solitude, in punishment for her difference.
She also had to stay in service to the princess, but that wasn't too bad, as it made her a friend.
"It's almost your birthday, I think?", Ivory asked, remembering that the princess's birthday was just a few days away. Kari nodded her head, a faintly sad glint in her pale blue eyes.
"It's worth celebrating, isn't it?"
No, Kari dodged the subject. Ivory knew that was a difficult topic for her. It was the day she was confined to her room and her mother was banished. Ivory was still a baby when that happened, but she remembered the indignation of the servants and the townspeople. She had heard that Queen Eirwen was a good queen, but she also had this strange ability to predict the future.
"Well... what would you like to do?", Ivory asked. Kari looked up with enthusiasm. She handed Ivory a paper. But when Ivory looked at it...
15 cm x 15 cm painting canvas
White, several shades of blue paint.
6 brushes of different sizes.
Easel
"It's worth getting, isn't it?"
"Okay. See you later?", Ivory suggested, standing up and making her way through the pile of papers and notebooks.
Kari nodded and sank back into her memories, wrapping herself in her thick blanket again.
She stepped out of the room with relief. The princess was finally stepping out of her comfort zone by asking for things that weren't her usual domain, like paint.
She walked back through the corridors, trying not to listen to the whispers of the maids.
"She's said to be possessed by Queen Eirwen, that's why she always goes to this room."
"She's heard that she eats children in this room."
"She resembles a man, doesn't she?"
She covered her ears, as trying to ignore them wasn't working. She headed towards the royal painter's room, which was located on the east wing, second door to the left.
Ivory approached the door, which was just as ornate as Kari's. It featured a white dragon, one of the six primordial dragons, said to have created Frostfell according to legend. It was fitting for the painter to display it on his door, as he loved the story.
She opened the door, expecting to find a normal scene. Splatters of paint everywhere, scattered pencils and papers in the room, easels covering every inch of the wall. Notably, she saw none of this. The room was spotless, and there was a red velvet background with a stool right in front of it. On the stool, Prince Aquilo was sitting for his portrait.
"Ah, good morning, Ivory! Are you here to see your future king sitting for a portrait?", asked Aquilo to Ivory, giving her a wink.
"Excuse me, little prince," replied Ivory, ignoring him partially as she looked for the objects her silent friend wanted. "I'm here just to pick up some supplies."
"Ah, is the little girl going to leave very quickly?", asked Aquilo, "But I wanted to see you!"
"Ah, not me". Ivory had found the art supplies from her list and placed them in a box she had found. "And I'm not a girl."
"Oh, my dear, you know very well that it's just a phase! It will pass when you grow up!", he muttered.
"I need to go," said Ivory, suddenly uneasy, because of the prince's words that reminded her of all the harm people said about her gender identity. I really want to get away from him.
"Are you leaving us already?" The Prince appeared at the door immediately, ignoring the complaints of the royal painter.
"That's not the behavior of a future king!", she scolded.
"Nobody will know. The others won't believe you, and the painter won't say anything if he wants to stay alive." He turned back to the painter for a second, then leaned in towards Ivory. "How about a romantic rendezvous?" Ivory shuddered. Of course, she had received many threats in the past, but never from a prince, especially not one who is heir to the throne.
"Don't you know what the word 'non' means?", she shot back, stepping aside to let the prince pass.
"Ah no", Aquilo replied with a smile. Obviously, the prince who gets everything he wants doesn't know what that word means.
Ivory rolled her eyes. "Why would you want a romantic rendezvous with me rather than with others? You must have a good hundred suitors?"
He interrupted her, still smiling: "500, to be exact". He tossed his hair back, sending it flying in the cold air.
"So, why me rather than someone else? I'm the palace's menace." Ivory wrapped her arms around her body.
"You're the prettiest girl I've ever seen." Aquilo placed his finger under his chin and forced Ivory to look at him.
